      <scopecontent id="aspace_432c117a5e6a21e27b028398c523854c">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The papers of Ralph McCallister (1905-) deal primarily with his association with the Chautauqua Institution, where he served as director of programs and education and as vice-president from 1944-1961. The correspondence, 1951-1961, is with both Chautauqua staff and summer visitors. There is a large section of letters to and from Rebecca Richmond, author of <title render="italic">
               <part>Invitation to Chautauqua</part>
            </title>. Mrs. Richmond was responsible for the creation of the Writers' Workshop and the Bell Tower scholarship at Chautauqua.</p>
         <p>McCallister resigned his post in 1961, objecting to the manner in which the Chautauqua Institution was being administered. There is a great deal of correspondence concerning the events which led to his retirement and public reaction to his decision to leave Chautauqua.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_d0f777dee1a0b28026b115fca532735d">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Ralph McCallister was born in Carmi, Illinois on September 28, 1905. He received his Ph.B. from the University of Chicago in 1930 and his M.A. from the University of Michigan in 1936. From 1936-1948 McCallister directed the Adult Education Council in Chicago. In 1944 he became the Director of Programs and Education, and Vice-President of the Chautauqua Institution, a position he held until 1961. Bewteen 1962 and 1970, McCallister coordinated many programs and projects in adult and higher education in the Carolinas and Virginia. In 1970 he became the Associate Director, Office of Medical Studies at the School of Medicine, University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.</p>  
      </bioghist>
